Typecasting : convert variable from one type to another type

Primitive type casting:
1. Widening Casting (automatically) / implicit - converting a smaller type to a larger type size
    byte -> short -> char -> int -> long -> float -> double

2. Narrowing Casting (manually) / explicit - converting a larger type to a smaller size type, must place the type in parentheses () in front of the value.
   int myInt = (int) myDouble;

Object type casting: through inheritance
1. Upcasting (automatically) / implicit - converting a subclass type to a superclass type
   Dog myDog = new Dog();
   Animal myAnimal = myDog;

2. Downcasting (manually) / explicit - converting a superclass type to a subclass type, must place the type in parentheses () in front of the value.
    Animal a = new Dog();
    Dog d = (Dog) a;
Note: Can throw ClassCastException, check with instanceof before downcasting
    if (a instanceof Dog) {
        Dog d = (Dog) a;
    } else {
        System.out.println("a is not an instance of Dog");
    }


Type Promotion in Java:
automatic conversion of smaller data types into a larger data type during arithmetic expressions.

byte  →
short →  promoted to int
char  →

Example : byte a = 10;
          byte b = 20;
          int c = a + b;   // Result is int

If one operand is larger, result becomes the larger type

